<p>8. Which of the following is mentioned as a normal physical sign of anger?<br>
A. Losing appetite for food<br>
B. Falling asleep suddenly<br>
C. Feeling cold and shivering<br>
D. Fast heartbeat and tense muscles</p>

<p>9. Which of these is a harmful effect of uncontrolled anger?<br>
A. Making du‘a more often<br>
B. Studying harder for exams<br>
C. Spending more time with family<br>
D. Holding grudges and cutting off ties</p>

<p>10. According to the hadith, who is the truly strong person?<br>
A. The fastest runner in battle<br>
B. The one with the loudest voice<br>
C. The one who controls himself when he is angry<br>
D. The one who can overpower others in wrestling</p>

<p>11. Scholars explain “Do not get angry” to mean:<br>
A. Never show any emotion<br>
B. Remove anger completely from your heart<br>
C. Pretend to be nonchalant in front of people<br>
D. Do not act upon your anger and remove its causes</p>

<p>12. If a person becomes angry while standing, he should:<br>
A. Sit down<br>
B. Jump up and down<br>
C. Start walking faster<br>
D. Run away immediately</p>

<p>13. According to the hadith of Abu Sa‘id al‑Khudri and Abu Hurayrah, which of the following can be a means for Allah to wipe away a Muslim’s sins?<br>
A. Any financial loss<br>
B. Any major illnesses<br>
C. Any illness, worry, sorrow, and distress<br>
D. Any emotional sadness, not physical pain</p>

<p>14. What two body parts are mentioned in the hadith, “Whoever guarantees for me what is between his jaws and what is between his legs, I guarantee Paradise for him”?<br>
A. Eyes and ears<br>
B. Hands and feet<br>
C. Heart and mind<br>
D. Tongue and private parts</p>

<p>15. How should a young Muslim view bad and inappropriate jokes?<br>
A. “Its not that deep”<br>
B. “Its something to be ignored”<br>
C. “Its something that’s need to be avoided”<br>
D. “Its just for the sake of entertainment, no big deal”</p>

<p>16. What does it mean that other Muslims are “safe” from a person’s tongue?<br>
A. He never speaks at all<br>
B. He always agrees with them<br>
C. He keeps every secret hidden<br>
D. He does not harm them with insults</p>

<p>17. What everyday behaviour can turn a person into a type of liar?<br>
A. Speaking constantly<br>
B. Posting to social media<br>
C. Keeping quiet everytime<br>
D. Sharing everything heard</p>

<p>18. What promise is given to the one who conceals the faults of a fellow Muslim?<br>
A. Allah will conceal his faults.<br>
B. People will love him in this world.<br>
C. He will share the sin because he hid the fault from others.<br>
D. He will be tested with the same fault because he did not expose it.</p>

<p>19. The hadith “A man follows the religion of his close friend, so each one should look carefully whom he takes as a close friend” teaches that choosing friends should be:<br>
A. Forced<br>
B. Random<br>
C. Accidental<br>
D. Intentional</p>

<p>20. Which set of qualities best describes an ideal friend in Islam?<br>
A. Rich, famous, entertaining<br>
B. Comfortable to be around, trustworthy, loyal<br>
C. Same nationality, same school<br>
D. Good at sports and games</p>

<p>21. A friendship that starts unintentionally can become Islamic and purposeful if:<br>
A. You try to hide your faith in front of them<br>
B. You slowly shift the relationship toward helping each other obey Allah<br>
C. You avoid any talk about religion<br>
D. You compete to see who can sin more</p>

<p>22. Two friends quarrel and completely refuse to talk for 40 days. Which statement best summarises the Islamic view of this behaviour?<br>
A. It is encouraged to teach lessons<br>
B. It is neutral if they still pray<br>
C. It disobeys guidance to reconcile within three days<br>
D. It is only disliked, never sinful</p>

<p>23. When a friend faces financial hardship, which response best fulfils the spirit of Islamic rights of friendship?<br>
A. Advising them to find a new friend<br>
B. Telling them to “rely on Allah”<br>
C. Helping according to your ability<br>
D. Lending money with interest</p>

<p>24. In the hadith about du‘a for others, why might a wise believer make a lot of du‘a for friends in their absence?<br>
A. Because angels record it as gossip<br>
B. Because an angel asks for the same good<br>
C. Because friends will owe them money later<br>
D. Because it replaces obligatory worship</p>

<p>25. A person openly denies Islam but sometimes attends Islamic events for fun. Which label applies to them?<br>
A. Munaafiq in creed<br>
B. Believer with weak īmān<br>
C. Open kāfir, not a munaafiq<br>
D. Muslim with practical hypocrisy</p>

<p>26. Why did the Prophet ﷺ warn even against lying “as a joke” to make people laugh?<br>
A. Because jokes are haram in Islam<br>
B. Because it may lead to serious lying<br>
C. Because companions did not like jokes<br>
D. Because it destroys a person’s memory</p>

<p>27. Which of the following people falls under “breaking promises” as a sign of hypocrisy?<br>
A. Someone who promises to come but suddenly becomes sick<br>
B. Someone who generally fulfils promises but forgets once in a while<br>
C. Someone well‑known for making promises he never intends to keep<br>
D. Someone who promises to do something then discovers it is haram and stops</p>

<p>28. The famous hadith lists three main signs of a hypocrite: lying when speaking, breaking promises, and betraying trusts. A fourth sign mentioned in another narration is:<br>
A. Delaying salah until its time finishes<br>
B. Being harsh to parents<br>
C. Becoming immoral when arguing<br>
D. Forgetting to say bismillah</p>

<p>29. Why is “cursing one’s parents” counted among the major sins even when done indirectly?<br>
A. Because any words about parents are automatically haram<br>
B. Because provoking others to curse your parents leads to the same end result<br>
C. Because only parents may curse children<br>
D. Because it is mentioned in the same hadith as shirk</p>

<p>30. Which approach best reflects the prophetic aim behind teaching the signs of hypocrisy?<br>
A. Using them mainly to accuse others of nifāq<br>
B. Using them as a mirror for self‑inspection and repentance<br>
C. Using them to divide the community<br>
D. Using them to decide who can enter the masjid</p>

